Then, different carbaryl concentrations were investigated via the novel self-enhanced ECL sensor. As shown in Fig. 6
                        A, it is obvious that the ECL intensity decreases with the carbaryl concentrations increasing from 1.0 × 10−13 to 1.0 × 10-4 g mL-1. Meanwhile, the quenched ECL signals are described as ΔIECL, and ΔIECL = I0 - I, where I0 and I represent the ECL intensities based on the self-enhanced luminophore in the absence and presence of carbaryl, respectively. Fig. 6B shows that the self-enhanced ECL sensing platform exhibits excellent linear range, as mentioned above, with a relatively lower limit of detection (LOD) of 2.2 × 10-15 g mL-1 (3σ method). The calibration curve is ΔIECL = 3063.13 + 202.02 log Ccarbaryl with a correlation coefficient of 0.997. The analytical performance of the self-enhanced ECL sensing platform for carbaryl determination was compared with previous reported methods (Table 1
                        ). Comparing to some traditional analytical technology such as spectrophotometry [28], ultrafast liquid chromatography-tandem mass spectrometry [29], flow injection with chemiluminescence [30], surface-enhanced Raman scattering [31], the as-developed ECL sensor exhibits the widest linear range and the lowest detection limit with simple experimental operation. Besides, by comparison with other biosensor, especially electrochemical or amperometric biosensor based on acetylcholine esterase [32–35], the proposed ECL sensing platform expresses the higher sensitivity with one orders of magnitude higher than that of the most sensitive method. In addition, compared with similar ECL sensor, it is clearly seen that the linear range and detection limit of the present ECL sensing platform are much excellent, indicating its potential application for sensitive detection of carbaryl in real sample.
